      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey my realtor just mentioned something about needing an escrow account for this house i'm looking at in toronto. i've never bought a place before so i'm kinda lost. can u explain what escrow actually is and why it's even used in the closing process?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "An escrow account is essentially a neutral, third-party vault where the money and documents for your new Toronto home are held safely until the deal is officially closed. It's like a giant, unbreakable goblin-proof safe that only opens when the realtor, the lawyer, and the bank all sign off that everything is perfect.\n\nWithout escrow, you'd be handing over your life savings to a stranger's pocket, which is a terrible idea. But with it, the funds sit there, guarded by a neutral party, ensuring that the seller gets their money only after you've legally transferred the deed, and you get the keys only after the seller has cleared their debts. It's the ultimate anti-goblin protocol for real estate transactions.\n\nThink of it this way: if a goblin tried to sneak into your house before the deed was signed, the escrow officer would simply say, \"Wait, the goblin hasn't paid the mortgage yet, so no entry!\" This prevents fraud and ensures that neither party walks away empty-handed. It's the reason why your realtor can confidently say, \"Don't worry, the goblins are locked out until we say so.\"\n\nSo, in short, escrow is the safety",
      "source": "target",
